Runesmithing (The Art of Eternal Marking)
Role in the Golden Age:
Runesmiths were among the most revered craftsmen in Aetheria. They did not merely enchant objects — they wrote permanence into reality. A master runesmith could carve symbols that made walls unbreakable for millennia, weapons that never dulled, or entire cities whose foundations actively repaired themselves. Dwarven holds, floating citadels, and ancient war machines all relied on their work. Runesmithing was the backbone of Golden Age engineering and architecture.
Magic Schools Combined:

Rune / Inscription Magic (absolute core) — The creation and binding of permanent magical sigils.
Aetherforge Magic — Infusing runes with raw Aetherite crystal essence.
Earth & Fire Elemental — Binding runes into stone and metal.
Abjuration — Creating defensive and stabilizing runes.
Soul Magic (advanced) — Binding intent, oaths, or minor spirits into the rune matrix.
Transmutation — Altering the physical properties of the material to better accept the rune.

Surface Analysis Today:
Runesmithing is one of the few high arts that still survives in a very rare and weakened form but functional, especially among dwarves. The very few modern runesmiths can create durable weapons, armor, and structural reinforcements that last decades or centuries. However, the complexity and power are greatly diminished.

Most current runes are simple: strengthening, sharpening, fire resistance, or basic warding.
True self-repairing or intelligent runes are extremely rare and usually found only on ancient relics.
Dwarven holds still train apprentices rigorously, but the loss of high-level Aetherforge knowledge means modern runes consume far more mana and are prone to “fading” over time.
Independent human and elven runesmiths exist but are considered inferior to dwarven masters.

Runesmithing remains the most accessible “lost profession” and is highly valued by all kingdoms, especially on the demonic borders.

Enchanting (The Weaving of Temporary Glory)
Role in the Golden Age:
Enchanters were the artists and battlefield support of the arcane world. While Runesmiths created permanent power, Enchanters wove temporary but incredibly potent magic into objects, clothing, and even living beings. They created flying cloaks, blades that burned with starfire for hours, armor that healed the wearer mid-battle, and siege engines that could be “recharged” with fresh spells. Enchanting was fast, flexible, and highly creative.
Magic Schools Combined:

Transmutation (primary) — Temporarily altering an object’s properties.
Elemental Schools (Fire, Wind, Lightning, etc.) — Infusing active effects.
Abjuration — Temporary shields and protective fields.
Illusion — Glamours and deceptive enchantments.
Emotion & Dream Magic — Enchantments that affect the mind or morale.
Rune Magic (light) — Creating “charge slots” for reusable enchantments.

Surface Analysis Today:
Enchanting is rare but more common than runesmithing, remaining a high-magic profession, though it is still a shadow of its former self. Modern enchanters (often called Spellweavers or Charmcrafters) can temporarily empower weapons, armor, and tools, but the effects are short-lived (minutes to a few days at best).

Most enchanters work for armies, noble houses, or adventuring guilds, applying combat buffs before battles or expeditions.
Common enchantments include: edge sharpening, minor elemental damage, lightening of weight, or basic protection runes.
The greatest limitation is the loss of multi-layering and rechargeable matrices — today, stacking too many enchantments on one item usually causes it to explode or fail dramatically.
Elven enchanters are considered the most elegant, dwarven ones the most reliable, and human ones the most creative (and reckless).

Because enchanting is faster and cheaper than true runesmithing, it is the main way most kingdoms arm their elite troops and adventurers.

Alchemy (The Art of Transmutation and Perfection)
Role in the Golden Age:
Alchemists were the supreme material manipulators of Aetheria. They didn’t just brew potions — they sought to perfect matter itself. Legendary alchemists could turn lead into gold (temporarily or permanently), create elixirs of immortality, forge living metals, distill pure mana into liquid form, and produce artifacts that blurred the line between magic and science. Flying ships ran on alchemical fuel, golem cores were stabilized with alchemical fluids, and entire armies marched with enhancement potions that made soldiers temporarily superhuman.
Magic Schools Combined:

Transmutation (absolute core) — The fundamental changing of one substance into another.
Aetherforge Magic — Purifying and concentrating raw mana into stable forms.
Elemental Magic (all four primary + advanced) — Precise control and combination of elements.
Blood & Soul Magic — Creating potions that affect life force, longevity, or the soul.
Nature & Poison — Extracting essences from rare plants, monsters, and crystals.
Rune / Inscription Magic — Stabilizing potions into permanent or long-lasting forms.

Surface Analysis Today:
Alchemy is one of the most widespread and practical surviving high arts, though greatly weakened. Modern alchemists are respected (and wealthy) professionals found in almost every major city and army.

Common creations: Healing potions, strength/mana boosters, poisons, explosive vials, and basic transmutations (e.g., cheap metal into better quality).
True transmutation of base metals into gold is extremely difficult and unstable — usually only possible in small quantities and for short durations.
The most valuable modern alchemists specialize in combat alchemy (potions thrown in battle) and refinement (improving existing materials).
Dwarves and humans dominate practical battlefield alchemy, while elves focus on refined, long-lasting elixirs.
The loss of high-level formulas means many legendary potions (true immortality, permanent attribute increases) can no longer be made.

Alchemy remains highly profitable. A skilled alchemist is often richer than minor nobles.

Apothecary (The Art of Earthly Medicine)
Role in the Golden Age:
Apothecaries (also called Life-Weavers or Herb-Masters) were the backbone of everyday health and battlefield survival. While the most gifted among them collaborated with Holy and Soul magic users for miraculous cures, the majority practiced highly advanced herbalism, physiology, and mana-flow manipulation. They created potent medicines, treated battlefield wounds, neutralized poisons, and developed treatments that could keep even severely injured warriors alive long enough for greater healing magic to take effect.
Magic Schools Combined:

Nature Magic (primary – plant essences and growth acceleration)
Water Magic (fluid balance and blood purification)
Basic Mana Flow Control (guiding internal energy to aid recovery)
Transmutation (refining herbs into concentrated medicines)

Surface Analysis Today:
Apothecaries are the most common healing professionals in Aetheria. They function as medieval-style medics with deep knowledge of herbalism, anatomy, and practical medicine.

They brew herbal remedies, salves, poultices, painkillers, antitoxins, and fever treatments.
Skilled apothecaries use minor mana flow techniques to enhance the potency of their medicines or gently guide a patient’s natural recovery.
They set bones, stitch wounds, treat infections, and manage long-term illnesses.
Unlike Holy magic users (who are rare and usually tied to churches or major Adventurer Guild branches), apothecaries are widespread and accessible. Almost every town and village has at least one.

Current Standing:

Most apothecaries receive formal training through guild apprenticeships or family traditions.
They are respected but not glorified — seen as essential craftsmen rather than miracle workers.
Battlefield apothecaries are extremely valuable to armies and adventuring parties, often carrying large kits of emergency medicines.
Holy magic users (rare) are usually employed by temples or large guilds and focus on dramatic, magical healing, while apothecaries handle the majority of day-to-day and follow-up care.

Apothecaries represent the grounded, practical side of healing in a world where true miracle magic is scarce.

Holy Healers (The Art of Divine Restoration)
Role in the Golden Age:
Holy Healers were the pinnacle of healing magic. While Apothecaries handled everyday medicine and Alchemists created supportive elixirs, Holy Healers performed true miracles of restoration. They could close mortal wounds in seconds, purge demonic corruption, regrow lost limbs, cure incurable diseases, and even bring back the recently dead if assisted by Soul Forgers. Temples and armies alike relied on them as living embodiments of the gods’ mercy on the battlefield and in daily life.
Magic Schools Combined:

Holy / Light Magic (absolute core) — Pure restorative and purifying energy.
Nature Magic — Supporting life force and cellular regeneration.
Soul Magic — Repairing damage to the spirit and preventing soul degradation.
Water Magic — Manipulating blood, bodily fluids, and life essence.
Emotion Magic (minor) — Calming pain and trauma of the mind.

Surface Analysis Today:
Profession Name: Holy Healers
Holy Healers are the rarest and most revered type of healer in modern Aetheria. Because Holy Magic aptitude is exceptionally uncommon, true Holy Healers are highly prized and rarely seen outside major temples or powerful organizations.
Current Standing:

Most Holy Healers are employed by temples of the Twelve (especially those dedicated to Elyndra or Lunareth) or by large Adventurer Guild branches.
They focus exclusively on magical healing — closing deep wounds, expelling poisons and curses, restoring lost limbs (though imperfectly), and treating magical or demonic afflictions.
They do not usually handle herbalism, surgery, or long-term care. That role belongs to Apothecaries.
A single skilled Holy Healers can keep an entire adventuring party or elite knight unit alive through brutal battles.
Because Holy Magic is rare, most Holy Healers are deeply religious and see their power as a divine calling rather than just a profession.

Limitations in the Current Age:

Healing is slower and less complete than in the Golden Age. Regrowing a full arm might take multiple sessions over days and still leave scars.
Resurrection is impossible without very rare artifacts or multiple Holy Healers working together and with the person having recently killed or died (only for the most powerful of rulers).
They are extremely vulnerable to exhaustion — channeling Holy Magic drains the healer significantly.
Many kingdoms and guilds offer huge incentives (land, titles, protection) to recruit and retain them.

Social Status:
Holy Healers are treated with immense respect (and sometimes fear). Common folk see them as living saints. Nobles and March lords compete fiercely for their service. Some Holy Healers become influential figures within the church hierarchy, while others prefer the freedom (and danger) of traveling with elite adventurer parties.

