Agricultural & Rural Professions

Peasant Farmer / Serf: The largest group. Grow wheat, barley, vegetables, and raise livestock. Most are tied to the land and owe labor or taxes to their lord.
Herdsman: Tend sheep, goats, cattle, or hardy frontier cattle. Common in marches and Beastkin borderlands.
Woodcutter / Forester: Harvest timber (dangerous near elven or corrupted forests).

----------

Artisan & Craft Professions

Blacksmith: Make tools, horseshoes, weapons, and armor. Highly respected. Dwarven-trained smiths are the best.
Carpenter / Woodworker: Build houses, wagons, furniture, and siege engines.
Tailor / Weaver: Make clothing, sails, and banners. Elven silk or enchanted thread commands high prices.
Leatherworker: Produce armor, saddles, boots, and belts. Very important for adventurers.
Mason / Stonecutter: Build walls, castles, and houses. Dwarven masons are legendary.
Brewer / Distiller: Make ale, mead, and strong spirits. A good brewer is loved by everyone.
Baker: Produce bread and pastries — often one of the more prosperous village professions.

---------

Trade & Service Professions

Merchant / Trader: Buy and sell goods. The successful ones join the Azure Accord.
Innkeeper / Tavern Owner: Run inns and taverns — hubs of gossip, rumors, and quests.
Cook / Chef: Work in noble houses, inns, or adventuring companies. Beastkin and Halfling cooks are prized.
Teamster / Caravan Driver: Transport goods across dangerous roads.
Miner: Extremely dangerous but well-paid. Many work in dwarven or human mines.

---------

Military & Security Professions

Man-at-Arms / Soldier: Professional or conscripted fighters. Serve lords or march garrisons.
Guard / Watchman: Town or city law enforcement.
Hedge Knight / Sworn Sword: Landless knights who sell their sword.
Scout / Ranger: Track enemies, monsters, or game. Often Beastkin or humans from border regions.
Bounty Hunter: Hunt criminals, escaped slaves, or monsters for coin.

----------

Specialized / Niche Professions

Scribe / Clerk: Read, write, and keep records (literacy is not common).
Herbalist (non-magical apothecary assistant): Gathers and prepares basic herbs.
Tanner: Treat hides (smelly but necessary).
Glassblower: Glass making.
Cartographer: Map roads, ruins, and borders (highly valued by guilds and armies).
Prostitute / Courtesan: Common in larger towns and cities. Some are guild-protected.
** gravedigger / Undertaker**: Handle the dead (often linked to Nythera worship).

----------

Hunting & Wilderness Professions

Hunter / Trapper: Tracks, hunts, and traps wild game, monsters, and fur-bearing animals. Highly valued in border regions and forests. Many are semi-nomadic and sell meat, pelts, and monster parts to villages or guilds.
Poacher: Illegal hunters who hunt on noble lands. Dangerous but profitable. Often become outlaws or hedge scouts.
Falconer: Trains and handles birds of prey for hunting (popular among nobility).
Guide / Pathfinder: Leads caravans or warbands through dangerous wilds.

---------

Food & Resource Professions

Miller: Operates water or wind mills to grind grain into flour. Often one of the wealthiest people in a village.
Baker: Produces bread, pies, and baked goods (usually works with the miller).
Butcher: Slaughters animals and preserves meat. Respected but considered “unclean” by some.
Fisherman / Netmaker: Works rivers, lakes, or coastal waters.
Beekeeper: Produces honey, wax, and mead. Often has minor herbal knowledge.

---------

Craft & Construction Professions

Cooper: Makes barrels, casks, and buckets (very important for storage and trade).
Thatcher: Builds and repairs thatched roofs.
Wheelwright: Builds and repairs wagon/cart wheels.
Fletcher: Makes arrows and crossbow bolts.
Bowyer: Crafts bows and longbows.
Cobbler / Shoemaker: Makes and repairs boots and shoes.
Chandler: Makes candles, soap, and tallow products.
Potter: Creates pottery and some ceramic goods.

----------

Service & Medical Professions

Barber-Surgeon: Cuts hair, pulls teeth, performs basic surgeries, bloodletting, and minor wound treatment. Common in towns.
Midwife: Assists with childbirth and women’s health. Often has herbal knowledge.
Wet Nurse: Breastfeeds noble or wealthy children when mothers cannot.

----------

Administrative & Civic Professions

Town Crier / Herald: Announces news, laws, and royal decrees.
Tax Collector: Hated but necessary. Often works for lords or kingdoms.
Clerk / Scribe: Keeps records, writes letters, and manages accounts.
Judge / Magistrate: Resolves disputes in villages or small towns (usually appointed by a lord).
Executioner: Carries out punishments and executions. Feared and socially isolated.

---------

Most of these professions are hereditary — passed down through families.
Many combine roles (e.g., a farmer might also be a hunter or thatcher in winter).
Hunters are especially important in frontier and march territories because they provide meat and valuable monster materials to the Veilwardens and Bloodfang guilds.
Barber-Surgeons and Apothecaries are the closest most common people get to medical care.
Professions like Miller, Cooper, and Blacksmith tend to be more prosperous than pure farmers.
